article.description:
Katie Smith scored 17 points and Svetlana Abrosimova added 15 to lead the host Minnesota Lynx past the Charlotte
Sting 73-67 on Saturday night.
article.headline: Charlotte drops to 0-3 on the road
article.linkText: Smith, Abrosimova lead Lynx past visiting Sting
article.story:
MINNEAPOLIS (AP) -- Katie Smith scored 17 points and Svetlana
Abrosimova added 15 to lead the Minnesota Lynx past the Charlotte
Sting 73-67 Saturday night.

Tammy Sutton-Brown scored 14 points, and Tangela Smith and
Tynesha Lewis had 11 apiece for the Sting, who fell to 0-3 on the
road.

Minnesota posts Nicole Ohlde and Vanessa Hayden, first-round
draft-picks in 2004 who started together for the first time this
season, combined for 24 points and 12 rebounds. Hayden keyed a
second-half surge with six blocked shots.

The 6-foot-5 Hayden scored eight of her 10 points in the second
half while the 6-4 Ohlde slashed her way to 14 points and six
rebounds.

"At 6-5 and 6-4, they just complement each other very well,"
Lynx coach Suzie McConnell Serio said. "Vanessa is so physical,
while Ohlde is more of a finesse player, and they play well
together."

While Ohlde started every game of her rookie year, Hayden came
into training camp with a foot injury and started just one game as
she tried to play her way back into shape.

Abrosimova finished 6-for-9 from the field and Minnesota (2-3)
shot 54 percent overall. Smith, who also had a team-high six
assists, hit 5 of 6 free throws down the stretch to secure the win.

"We had great balance scoring, inside and outside, up and down
the stat sheet," McConnell Serio said. "Svetlana was just Svet
being Svet, making things happen all over the court and making
timely baskets."

Charlotte (1-5) trailed by 10 late in the first half but closed
the half on a 13-4 run to trail 35-34 at the break. They stayed
close throughout the second half, but Hayden came through with big
plays on both ends of the court to help the Lynx pull away.

Hayden made a hook shot in the lane, then blocked a shot on the
other end to trigger a fast-break layup by Abrosimova, putting
Minnesota ahead 57-50 with 5:47 left. The Sting missed three free
throws in the next 2 minutes and didn't draw closer than five the
rest of the way.

"Hopefully, this is just our slump we're going through right
now, and we're getting it out of our way early," Tangela Smith
said. "It's not how you start, it's how you finish."
